		<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn">Bill McIninch</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	 	</div><!-- end .comment-author -->

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="http://hackaday.com/2013/09/23/guest-rant-ham-radio-hackers-paradise/comment-page-1/#comment-1065155">September 25, 2013 at 8:42 am</a>
					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>The ARRL does not issue licenses.  Only the FCC does that.  The licensing system uses unpaid volunteers who are certified through any of several groups (in my case, 2 different ones, ARRL and W5YI) and are legally responsible to keep the exams honest.  Since I can&#8217;t pay a $10,000 fine and don&#8217;t care to lose my license for a decade, I make sure to give applicants exactly the grade they merit.<br />
The ARRL is simply the largest of several ham radio groups around the world.  The membership fee mainly gets you a magazine subscription and regular reminders to congress that there are over 700,000 Americans who care about who uses what frequencies.</p>
