					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>It&#8217;s not a US thing.  Since radio waves don&#8217;t respect national boundaries, there have been rules and licensing regulations in place by international treaties since at least 1906.  It didn&#8217;t take long for radio users to realize that coordination was needed, or else a few bad operators would spoil the bands for everyone.  </p>
<p><a href="http://www.itu.int/ITU-R/index.asp?category=information&#038;rlink=promotion-100-years&#038;lang=en" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">http://www.itu.int/ITU-R/index.asp?category=information&#038;rlink=promotion-100-years&#038;lang=en</a></p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/09/23/guest-rant-ham-radio-hackers-paradise/?replytocom=1063859#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-1063859", "1063859", "respond", "103405")'>Reply</a><span class="safe-comments-report-link">
