	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-1063647">

		
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn">Justin</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	 	</div><!-- end .comment-author -->

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="http://hackaday.com/2013/09/23/guest-rant-ham-radio-hackers-paradise/comment-page-1/#comment-1063647">September 23, 2013 at 10:39 am</a>
					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Tom<br />
CW is no longer required for achieving a ham radio license.  If you want more information about how to get involved, visit <a href="http://www.arrl.org/getting-licensed" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">http://www.arrl.org/getting-licensed</a>.  There are three different licenses available for Radio Amateurs.  The Technician class license, the first in the sequence, gives you access to the VHF and UHF bands and a small portion of the 10m frequency band.  This is mostly used for local communications, as well as satellites, moon-bounce, and remote control.  The next level gives you access to long distance communication in the 10m through 180m bands.  This allows round the world transmission.  <a href="http://www.arrl.org/graphical-frequency-allocations" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">http://www.arrl.org/graphical-frequency-allocations</a><br />
Most hams tend to be very friendly about their hobby and they aren&#8217;t all older.  I am part of a college ham radio group that consists of engineers in their twenties.</p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/09/23/guest-rant-ham-radio-hackers-paradise/?replytocom=1063647#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-1063647", "1063647", "respond", "103405")'>Reply</a><span class="safe-comments-report-link">
