	<li class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-1063652">

		
		<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn"><a href='http://kr0siv.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>KR0SIV</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	 	</div><!-- end .comment-author -->

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
			<a href="http://hackaday.com/2013/09/23/guest-rant-ham-radio-hackers-paradise/comment-page-1/#comment-1063652">September 23, 2013 at 10:43 am</a>
					</div><!-- end .comment-meta -->

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Becoming a ham is very easy these days.</p>
<p>To take your test you need to find a club, most clubs have VEs (examiners) who can give you the test. The ARRL has a great search tool to find local clubs, keep in mind there are clubs not working with the ARRL so Google is another good place to look.</p>
<p>ARRL Club Search: <a href="http://www.arrl.org/find-a-club" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">http://www.arrl.org/find-a-club</a></p>
<p>The test is about $14USD to take and if time is available if you pass your technician class (the lowest class available) you can take the next two class tests at no extra charge.</p>
<p>There are 3 classes.</p>
<p>Technician: UHF/VHF Bands- Local communications with a small 10m band HF portion.<br />
General: All the radio bands except for a few dedicated CW spaces on HF.<br />
Extra: You get those extra CW spaces, and you can become a VE yourself.</p>
<p>I went to <a href="http://hamtestonline.com" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">http://hamtestonline.com</a> to take my practice exams, but QRZ has free practice tests if you don&#8217;t want to pay the hamtestonline fees.</p>
<p>Any questions feel free to ask me! kr0siv at amateurcq.com</p>
		</div><!-- end .comment-content -->

